---
import AcademicLayout from '../layouts/AcademicLayout.astro';
import { Code } from 'astro:components';
import fs from 'node:fs';
import path from 'node:path';

const title = "Methodology: The Calculus of 'Deaditude'";
const abstract =
  'This document outlines the rigorous mathematical and statistical models utilized to calculate the Deaditude Score of software technologies, based directly on the scoring engine implementation.';

// Read the engine python code directly from the local monorepo
let engineSnippet = '';
try {
  const enginePath = path.resolve(process.cwd(), '../deaditude/engine/scoring/scoring.py');
  const pythonCode = fs.readFileSync(enginePath, 'utf8');

  // Extract the calculate_deaditude_score function block
  const match = pythonCode.match(/def calculate_deaditude_score[\s\S]*?(?=\n# ---|\nif __name__)/);
  if (match) {
    engineSnippet = match[0].trim();
  } else {
    engineSnippet =
      'def calculate_deaditude_score():\n    # Could not extract function from scoring.py';
  }
} catch (e) {
  engineSnippet = '# Error loading live engine code. Please try again later.';
}
---

<AcademicLayout title={title} abstract={abstract}>
  <section>
    <h2>1. Introduction</h2>
    <p>
      Determining whether a technology is "dead" requires moving beyond subjective developer
      opinions, Reddit flamewars, and Hacker News echo chambers into empirical data analysis. The
      Deaditude Engine aggregates signals across seven key dimensions to compute a unified score
      with a statistical confidence interval.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>2. Data Sources & Weighting</h2>
    <p>
      The engine calculates a weighted average of individual deaditude scores from various sources.
      Because the lifecycle of a new framework looks very different from an established enterprise
      language, the weights adapt dynamically based on the technology's age.
    </p>

    <h3>2.1 Base Weights (Established Tech &gt; 5 years)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>GitHub (20%):</strong> Codebase activity, commits, and issue resolution.</li>
      <li><strong>Google Jobs (20%):</strong> Employer demand and active job listings.</li>
      <li><strong>Reddit (15%):</strong> Community sentiment and discussion volume.</li>
      <li><strong>StackShare (15%):</strong> Corporate adoption and stack inclusion.</li>
      <li>
        <strong>YouTube (15%):</strong> Learning resources, tutorials, and content creator hype.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>StackOverflow (10%):</strong> Developer support and "despair index" of unanswered questions.
      </li>
      <li><strong>Hacker News (5%):</strong> Intellectual discourse and trending topics.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2.2 Young Tech Weights (Age &le; 5 years)</h3>
    <p>
      Brand new technologies inherently lack massive enterprise job demand and StackShare adoption.
      To compensate, the engine heavily weights community hype, open-source activity, and content
      creation:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>GitHub:</strong> Increased to 25%</li>
      <li><strong>Reddit:</strong> Increased to 20%</li>
      <li><strong>YouTube:</strong> Increased to 20%</li>
      <li><strong>Google Jobs:</strong> Decreased to 10%</li>
      <li><strong>StackShare:</strong> Decreased to 10%</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>3. The Scoring Algorithm</h2>
    <p>
      The Deaditude calculation is not a naive average. It factors in data quality, variance, and
      age-based generosity. The overarching formula that calculates the final Deaditude Score
      percentage (<i>D</i>) is defined as:
    </p>

    <div
      style="text-align: center; margin: 3rem 0; font-size: 1.6rem; padding: 2rem; border: 2px solid var(--body-color); border-radius: 4px; box-shadow: 4px 4px 0 var(--body-color);"
    >
      <i
        >D = 10 &times; G<sub>age</sub> &times; &sum;<sub>i=1</sub><sup>7</sup> (W<sub>eff, i</sub> &times;
        S<sub>i</sub>)</i
      >
    </div>

    <p>
      Where: <br />
      <strong><i>G<sub>age</sub></i></strong> = Age Generosity Multiplier (0.85, 0.90, or 1.0)<br />
      <strong><i>W<sub>eff, i</sub></i></strong> = The normalized effective weight of the <i>i</i
      >-th data source<br />
      <strong><i>S<sub>i</sub></i></strong> = The raw deaditude score (0-10) of the <i>i</i>-th data
      source
    </p>

    <h3>3.1 Quality Degradation & Effective Weights</h3>
    <p>
      Each metric source returns a raw deaditude score (0-10) and a <em>quality factor</em> (<i>q</i
      > &isin; [0, 1]). If an API fails or data is sparse, <i>q</i> drops. The base weight is multiplied
      by <i>q</i> to form the <em>effective weight</em> (<i>W<sub>eff</sub></i>), which is then
      re-normalized across all 7 sources.
    </p>

    <h3>3.2 Age Generosity Multiplier</h3>
    <p>
      New technologies are afforded a "grace period" to mature, while older technologies that have
      survived over a decade are evaluated strictly on their current momentum. Before the final
      score is converted to a percentage, a generosity multiplier is applied:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Young (&le; 5 years):</strong> Score &times; 0.85</li>
      <li><strong>Maturing (&le; 10 years):</strong> Score &times; 0.90</li>
      <li><strong>Established (&gt; 10 years):</strong> Score &times; 1.0</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>3.3 Confidence Intervals</h3>
    <p>
      We use a variance model to compute a 95% Confidence Interval. The measurement standard
      deviation (&sigma;) for a source is inversely proportional to its data quality:
    </p>
    <div style="text-align: center; margin: 2rem 0; font-size: 1.2rem;">
      <i
        >&sigma; = &sigma;<sub>base</sub> / &radic;<span style="text-decoration: overline">q</span
        ></i
      >
    </div>
    <p>
      If data quality is zero, &sigma; doubles to reflect high uncertainty. The overall variance is
      the sum of the squared effective weights multiplied by their respective variances, allowing
      the engine to mathematically express its uncertainty when data is missing or low-quality.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>4. Engine Implementation (Live Code)</h2>
    <p>
      For full transparency, here is the exact <b>live, auto-synced</b> algorithm running in the backend
      Python engine right now that computes the final percentage and confidence bounds. Click the code
      below to view the full source file on GitHub:
    </p>
    <a
      href="https://github.com/jobehi/isThisTechDead/blob/main/deaditude/engine/scoring/scoring.py"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener noreferrer"
      style="text-decoration: none; color: inherit; display: block; transition: transform 0.2s ease, box-shadow 0.2s ease;"
      onmouseover="this.style.transform='translateY(-2px)';"
      onmouseout="this.style.transform='translateY(0)';"
      title="View scoring.py on GitHub"
    >
      <Code
        code={engineSnippet}
        lang="python"
        theme="github-dark"
        wrap={false}
        class="methodology-code"
      />
    </a>
  </section>

  <style>
    .methodology-code {
      margin-bottom: 2rem;
      cursor: pointer;
      border-radius: 8px !important;
      overflow: hidden;
      box-shadow: 0 4px 6px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
      padding: 1.5rem !important;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      line-height: 1.5;
      margin-top: 0 !important;
    }
  </style>
</AcademicLayout>
